          "body": "The mother's response to the first cub's capture is not repentance but repetition (vv. 5-9). She 'waited in hope' (*yachal*) — the word carries overtones of expectant longing — and when that hope proved lost, she took another cub and made him a young lion. The parallel structure of the second prince's story (vv. 6-9) is deliberate: same verbs, same trajectory, same end. But the second story is expanded — he prowls among the lions, his devastation is wider (fortified towers, laid-waste cities, v. 7), his roaring is louder (the land itself is appalled). And the coalition against him is greater: not one nation but many, 'on every side from their provinces' (v. 8), spreading a net. Most commentators identify this figure as Jehoiachin (2 Kings 24:8-16) or Zedekiah (2 Kings 24:18-25:7). The expansion of destruction in the second figure suggests Zedekiah, whose eleven-year reign ended in the siege of Jerusalem and his blinding at Riblah by Nebuchadnezzar. Either way, the pattern is sealed: the second attempt to produce a worthy heir repeats the devour-and-be-devoured cycle without correction."
