          "title": "The vine — dynastic potential and its uprooting",
          "body": "The chapter's second panel shifts from the lion allegory to the vine allegory (vv. 10-14), and the shift in metaphor is itself meaningful. The vine image in the Old Testament carries specific covenantal resonance: in Psalm 80:8-16, God brought a vine out of Egypt, planted it, and it filled the land; in Isaiah 5:1-7, the beloved's vineyard is a figure for Israel's failure; in Hosea 10:1, Israel is a luxuriant vine. Ezekiel has already used vine imagery in chapter 15 (the vine fit only for burning) and chapter 17 (the vine transplanted by the eagle). Here in chapter 19, the vine is the mother herself — the dynastic institution — and her branches are the rulers she produced. The description of the vine in its prime (vv. 10-11) is among the most generous passages in the chapter: planted by abundant waters, fruitful, full of branches, towering above the clouds, visible in its height. This was a real potential. The dynasty had genuine resources for righteous rule. The uprooting (v. 12) arrives not as a natural decline but as an act of violent intervention: 'plucked up in fury' — the east wind of Babylon's desert blast desiccating what the covenant waters had sustained."
