          "title": "Fire from its own branch — self-destruction as judgment",
          "body": "The vine panel closes with an image unique in the chapter: 'fire has gone out from its branch' (v. 14). This is not the east wind alone, not only Babylon's armies from without — the fire starts within the vine itself. Most commentators connect this to Zedekiah's oath-breaking described in chapter 17: the king who swore a covenant oath to Babylon and violated it, thereby bringing the full force of divine judgment (17:16-20). The fire of political treachery, of self-serving rebellion, goes out from the very royal branch that should have been a scepter, and it consumes the shoots and fruit. The dynasty becomes its own executioner. This is the chapter's most searching theological moment: judgment is not only an external imposition but the natural harvest of internal corruption. The dynasty that devoured men finds that its own rulers devour the dynasty. The closing verdict — 'there is not in it a strong branch, a scepter to rule' — is the chapter's epitaph. The line of ruling potential is exhausted. The lament has become a lament."
